NDFSK Makes Public Slogans to Fight against "Motion on Impeachment" 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 19 (KCNA) -- The Information Department of the Central Committee of the National Democratic Front of South Korea on March 17 made public slogans for an immediate struggle against the "motion on impeachment against the president", according to the Internet site of Kuguk Jonson.
 Slogans said: The passage of the "motion on impeachment" through the National Assembly was a big political rebellion as it was an insult to the people's will and a disregard of them. The struggle against the impeachment should be carried to the end. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The "motion" railroaded through the NA against the people's mindset is null and void. The Constitutional Court should immediately turn down the "motion." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The railroading the "motion" through the NA was a parliamentary coup aimed at winning the "general election." Let us dissolve the political terror-ridden NA. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Let the progressive reform-minded forces judge the forces asserting impeachment by winning a victory in the "general election"! &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The backstage wirepuller of the "motion on impeachment" is the U.S. The U.S., stop interfering in others' internal affairs! &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Our people are not dead but alive. Let us lead the struggle against the impeachment to a victory in the "general election" with the courageous determination of the people!

Annual Meeting of DPRK-Cuba Solidarity Committee 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 19 (KCNA) -- An annual meeting of the DPRK-Cuba Solidarity Committee was held at the Taedonggang Club for the Diplomatic Corps here on March 18.
 The meeting reviewed the one-year-long work of the committee for friendship and solidarity with the Cuban people who are vigorously advancing along the road of independence and socialism against imperialism and discussed the action program for this year. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present were Kim Yong Jin, minister of Education who is chairman of the DPRK-Cuba Solidarity Committee, Jon Hyon Chan, vice-chairman of the Korean Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries, and members of the solidarity committee. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The staff members of the Cuban embassy in Pyongyang were on hand.

KCNA Slams U.S. for Increasing Military Tension in Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 19 (KCNA) -- The U.S. is going to launch Foal Eagle joint military exercises and Reception, staging, onward movement and integration (RSOI) in south Korea, defying the demand of the Korean people and the international community for a peaceful solution to the nuclear issue between the DPRK and the U.S. and a settlement of the nuclear crisis on the Korean peninsula.
 According to a press report, the U.S. aircraft carrier Kitty Hawk entered Pusan Port, south Korea, on March 15 with about 70 fighters and 5,500 combatants aboard to participate in an exercise aimed to launch a nuclear war against the north. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A large-scale exercise of loading and unloading war supplies has been under way at Phyongthaek Port, Kyonggi Province, since March 8 with hundreds of military vehicles, tanks and amphibious armored cars belonging to a flotilla of U.S. marines. The drill participated in by at least 8,000 GIs of U.S. marines from Hawaii and Okinawa will reportedly last until April. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On March 12 the command of the 8th U.S. Army announced a plan to pay an allowance to the U.S. soldiers in south Korea as an incentive to lengthen the term of their service there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Such serious military moves of the U.S. forces in south Korea suggest that the day of the outbreak of a war is drawing near hour by hour in Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. has already staged various forms of war maneuvers one after another according to the war scenario based on the doctrine of "a preemptive attack" after shipping into south Korea the latest war hardware tested in the Afghan and Iraqi war. Recently, it conducted even a drill of evacuating families of U.S. servicemen and other Americans, something reminiscent of the eve of the last Korean war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It has been a usual practice for the U.S. to cite "threat to security" and "defense" as a pretext for kicking up a war racket but the recent developments have proved this is a sheer lie and the U.S. is chiefly to blame for the crisis. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. is hell-bent on the moves to isolate and stifle the DPRK politically, militarily and economically behind the curtain of dialogue for the settlement of the nuclear issue between them, working hard to plug Japan and its other allies. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is keen to ignite a war against the DPRK, while working hard to bring back to the era of confrontation the inter-Korean relations favorably developing in the direction of national reconciliation, peace and reunification of the country after the publication of the June 15 North-South Joint Declaration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. plans to stage large-scale war exercises through the massive transfer and deployment of its armed forces in its mainland and overseas and the mobilization of all the south Korean forces suggest what a dangerous political and military adventure it is going to make on the Korean peninsula.

KCNA Blasts Japanese Chief Executive's Reckless Remarks 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 19 (KCNA) -- The Japanese chief executive at an official meeting on March 15 reiterated his plan to continue his visit to the "Yasukuni Shrine."
 It was already known that at the meetings of the budgetary committees of the House of Representatives and the House of Councilors of Japan held on February 10 and March 9 he let loose a string of provocative remarks that "he had no will to change his view no matter what other countries might say" and "it was quite natural for a Japanese to visit the shrine" only to spark public criticism. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese reactionary ruling quarters' official visits to the shrine and such remarks intended to justify and institutionalize them indicate that they have become evermore undisguised in their moves to make a trend towards the Right prevail in the Japanese society and instill the idea of militarism into the Japanese people in a bid to lay an ideological foundation for overseas aggression. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This is an intolerable insult and mockery of the victims of the barbarous massacre and savage plunder perpetrated by the Japanese imperialists in the last century, their bereaved families and the Asian people and an open challenge to the just judgment meted out by history to the chief criminals in the war of aggression in the 20th century. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The shrine is a symbol of militarism as it is the place where top class war criminals who directly organized and ordered the start of the wars of aggression, massacre and unprecedented plunder are entombed. Therefore, visits of Japanese politicians to the shrine have been censured as grave criminal moves to revive militarism and lashed all Asian countries into fury. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese politicians who have so far asserted the visit to the shrine and gone there are without an exception the right-wing conservatives who have encouraged the revival of militarism and spearheaded it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The chief executive of Japan has linked visits to the shrine to the "tradition and religion of Japan." But this is not an issue related to the tradition and religion. This is rather a matter related to the Japanese authorities' political tendency and their attitude toward history. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Bowing to the memorial tablets of war criminals and praying for their soul can not be construed otherwise than a rash act to push ahead with the militarization in a bid to realize the old dream of the "Greater East Asia Co-prosperity Sphere" which they failed to do in the past. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 That was why whenever the chief executives of Japan paid official visits to the shrine in the past they touched off so strong public criticism at home and abroad and spawned serious political and diplomatic problems. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The present chief executive of Japan can never evade the responsibility for all the consequences to be entailed by his repeated visit to the shrine and his remarks justifying it.

